\details{
INCA runs a population of K parallel random-walk Metropolis (RWM) chains on
the GPU (in this interface, K is given by the argument \code{p}). Each chain
uses the same Gaussian random-walk proposal covariance, which is learned from
the pooled history of all particles.

\strong{Random-walk Metropolis.}
Given a current state theta, RWM proposes theta* = theta + xi with
xi distributed as N(0, Sigma_prop), and accepts with probability
alpha(theta, theta*) = min(1, f(theta*) / f(theta)). The proposal is
symmetric, so the Metropolis--Hastings ratio reduces to the target density
ratio.

\strong{Progress output (acceptance rate).}
During sampling, the implementation prints a progress line of the form
\sQuote{Executing iteration t of T (acceptance rate: ...)}. The acceptance
rate displayed at iteration \eqn{t} is the fraction of the \eqn{K} proposals
accepted at that iteration,
\deqn{\mathrm{ar}_t=\frac{1}{K}\sum_{k=1}^{K}\mathbf{1}\{\text{particle $k$ accepted at iteration $t$}\}.}{
ar_t = (1/K) * sum_{k=1}^K I(accepted at iteration t).
}
This is an iteration-level statistic (not a cumulative acceptance rate). The
last printed value corresponds to \eqn{t=T}{t=T} and is computed from the
\eqn{K} accept/reject outcomes at the final iteration.

\strong{Global (history-pooled) covariance learning.}
Let theta_t^(k) denote the state of particle k at iteration t. INCA maintains
running sums over all particles and (past) iterations:
S_t = \eqn{\sum_{s=1}^{t}\sum_{k=1}^{K}\theta_s^{(k)}}{sum_{s<=t,k} theta_s^(k)} and
Q_t = \eqn{\sum_{s=1}^{t}\sum_{k=1}^{K}\theta_s^{(k)}(\theta_s^{(k)})^{\top}}{sum_{s<=t,k} theta_s^(k) (theta_s^(k))^T}.
With n_t = K t, the pooled mean and (population) covariance are
\deqn{\bar{\theta}_t = \frac{1}{n_t}S_t,\qquad \widehat{\Sigma}_t = \frac{1}{n_t}Q_t - \bar{\theta}_t\bar{\theta}_t^{\top},}{
theta_bar_t = S_t / n_t,  Sigma_hat_t = Q_t / n_t - theta_bar_t theta_bar_t^T.
}

The proposal covariance is taken proportional to this pooled estimate and is
refreshed every \code{covit} iterations:
\deqn{\Sigma_{\mathrm{prop}} \;\propto\; \widehat{\Sigma}_t.}{Sigma_prop proportional to Sigma_hat_t.}
In the current implementation, the initial proposal covariance is isotropic
(proportional to the identity), and Cholesky factorisation is guarded by a
small diagonal jitter if needed for numerical stability in single precision.

\strong{Cholesky factorisation on the GPU.}
Gaussian proposal increments are generated via a Cholesky factor L with
Sigma_prop = L L^T, then xi = z L^T for z distributed as N(0, I_D). The implementation uses
NVIDIA cuSOLVER (\code{cusolverDnSpotrf}), cuRAND, and cuBLAS
(\code{cublasStrmm}) for this step.

The meaning and required layout of \code{GPUkernel}, \code{X} and \code{Xi}
depends on the target-density kernel being used. See \code{\link{cmcmc}} for
the currently documented kernels (including \code{"MVNorm"} and
\code{"Logistic"}, \code{"HierBetaBinomJoint"}, and \code{"NneWayNormalNC"})
and examples of how to construct \code{X} and \code{Xi}.

\strong{GPU kernels and data layout.}
The \code{GPUkernel}, \code{X}, and \code{Xi} conventions are the same as for
\code{\link{cmcmc}}. In particular, this package treats \code{X} as a flat
numeric vector (copied to the GPU as single-precision floats) and \code{Xi} as
a flat integer vector (copied as 32-bit integers). Currently documented
kernels include \code{"MVNorm"}, \code{"Logistic"}, \code{"HierBetaBinomJoint"},
and \code{"NneWayNormalNC"}; see \code{\link{cmcmc}} for the full per-kernel
layouts and R code snippets.
